title: Fix soldermask and drill layer ordering with explicit soldermask rendering and hover support
description: Fixes PCB rendering issues by making soldermask a first-class layer and correcting drillsilkscreen ordering across the canvas pipeline.
body:
This PR fixes multiple long-standing PCB rendering issues by making soldermask a first-class, explicitly rendered layer and correcting drill/silkscreen ordering across the canvas pipeline.

Core changes:

Upgrades circuit-to-canvas to v0.0.61 to pick up corrected hole/soldermask semantics.

Introduces drawSoldermaskElementsForLayer to explicitly render soldermask per layer instead of relying on side effects.

Fixes drill rendering so holes are drawn first, then properly covered by soldermask (with margins), matching real PCB fabrication behavior.

Corrects layer and z-order sequencing (silkscreen vs soldermask vs drill) in both CanvasPrimitiveRenderer and Drawer.

Propagates drawSoldermask consistently to vias and SMT pads so soldermask behavior is uniform.

Adds hover highlighting for soldermask openings on pads, vias, and plated holes.

Result: accurate soldermask coverage, correct drill visibility, proper silkscreen ordering, and predictable hover behavior across all PCB layers.

title: Support array pin sides with default directions

### Motivation
- Allow shorthand side definitions like `leftSide: string[]` or `topSide: number[]` when specifying schematic pin arrangements to make input more ergonomic. 
- Automatically derive a sensible `direction` for these shorthand arrays to ensure consistent layout without requiring explicit direction on every side. 
- Keep the public API backward compatible while accepting both the full object form and the simple array form for sides.

### Description
- Add `PinSideDefinitionInput` type and accept either a `PinSideDefinition` or an array of pin identifiers for each side. 
- Introduce `pinSideDefinitionWithDefaultDirection` Zod schema that transforms an input array into `{ pins, direction }` and wire it into `schematicPortArrangement` so `leftSide`/`rightSide` default to `"top-to-bottom"` and `topSide`/`bottomSide` default to `"left-to-right"`. 
- Add a unit test `should apply default directions for pin arrays` in `tests/chip2-schematic-port-arrangement.test.ts` and regenerate `generated/COMPONENT_TYPES.md` and `generated/PROPS_OVERVIEW.md` to reflect the new input type.

**Example and usage updates:**

title: Font Pipeline Refactor: Rebuild Glyph Parsing, Scaling, and Spacing with Arial-Accurate Metrics
description: Rebuilds the font generation pipeline to use metrics-driven architecture based on Arial glyph data, improving glyph parsing, scaling, and spacing accuracy.
body:
This PR is a large, structural refactor of the font generation pipeline, not a cosmetic tweak.

Scope of the refactor

Replaced the monospace-based glyph model with a metrics-driven architecture aligned to real Arial glyph data.

Split responsibilities cleanly:

SVG path parsing → polygon extraction

Boolean geometry resolution

Per-glyph scaling, translation, and baseline alignment

Final glyph construction with correct advance widths and side bearings

Rewrote SVG path parsing logic to correctly support implicit L commands, relative coordinates, compact paths, and malformed editor output.

Introduced Arial metrics ingestion (arial-metrics.json) and a generator script to source canonical measurements directly from the system font.

Refactored glyph layout logic to operate on advance width and bearings, not bounding-box centering.

Added fallback compatibility mode to preserve deterministic output when Arial metrics are unavailable.

Validation

Added visual regression tests comparing:

Glyph height ratios vs Arial

Adjacent letter spacing vs Arial

New snapshot outputs make spacing and baseline correctness immediately verifiable.

title: Allow via entries in trace pcbPath
description: Permit pcbPath route points to express vias so traces can include layer transitions in path descriptions and enforce validation rules for via-related inputs.
body:
### Motivation

- Permit pcbPath route points to express vias so traces can include layer transitions in path descriptions.
- Enforce that when a point is marked `via: true` it must declare a `toLayer`, and forbid layer fields on non-via points to prevent ambiguous input.

### Description

- Add a `pcbPathPoint` schema in `lib/components/trace.ts` that extends the existing `point` with `via?: boolean`, `fromLayer?: layer_ref`, and `toLayer?: layer_ref` and applies a `superRefine` to validate the via-related rules. 
- Replace the previous `pcbPath` type with an array of `pcbPathPoint | string` so string selectors remain supported. 
- Add a test `tests/trace.test.ts` to cover pcbPath entries containing a via with `toLayer` specified. 
- Regenerate documentation artifacts so `generated/COMPONENT_TYPES.md` reflects the new pcbPath/via shape.

### Testing

- Ran `bun test tests/trace.test.ts`, which passed 5 tests and 0 failures. 
- Ran `bunx tsc --noEmit` to typecheck the project, which completed successfully. 
- Ran the repository generation scripts (`scripts/generate-component-types.ts`, `scripts/generate-manual-edits-docs.ts`, `scripts/generate-readme-docs.ts`, `scripts/generate-props-overview.ts`) and `bun run format`, all of which completed without errors and updated generated documentation.
